<ul><li>Consider a simple pendulum consist of a bob of mass&nbsp;\(m\)&nbsp;attached to a thread of length&nbsp;\(L\).</li><li>At displacement&nbsp;\(s\)&nbsp;from the lowest point, the thread is at angle&nbsp;\(\theta\)&nbsp;to the vertical.</li><li>Its&nbsp;<b>weight</b>&nbsp;has components&nbsp;\(mg\cos\theta\)&nbsp;perpendicular to the path of the bob, and&nbsp;\(mg\sin\theta\)&nbsp;along the path&nbsp;<b>towards the equilibrium position</b>.</li><li>The restoring force is therefore&nbsp;\(F=-mg\sin\theta\)\[a=\frac{-mg\sin\theta}{m}=-g\sin\theta\]</li><li>For small&nbsp;\(\theta\),&nbsp;\(\sin\theta\approx\frac{s}{L}\)\[a=-\frac{g}{L}s=-\omega^2s\]</li><li>Therefore&nbsp;\(\omega^2=\frac{g}{L}\)</li></ul>